{"title_page": "List of Big Japan Pro Wrestling tournaments", "text_new": "[[Big Japan Pro Wrestling]] has held a variety of different [[professional wrestling tournament]]s, mainly in [[hardcore wrestling|deathmatch format]], competed for by sports entertainers that are a part of their [[Big Japan Pro Wrestling#Roster|roster]].\n\n==Sporadic tournaments==\n===BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship Tournament (1998)===\nThe '''BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship Tournament''' was an eight-man single-elimination tournament conducted on March 2, 1998 to crown the inaugural [[BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship (1998\u20132002)|BJW Junior Heavyweight Champion]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Junior Heavyweight Title Tournament 1998 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/title.html#junior |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{8TeamBracket-NoSeeds\n| RD1=Quarterfinals\n| RD2=Semifinals\n| RD3=Final\n| RD1-team1 = '''[[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]'''\n| RD1-team2 = [[Gran Naniwa]]\n| RD1-score1 = Pin\n| RD1-score2 =\n| RD1-team3 = '''[[Minoru Tanaka (wrestler)|Minoru Tanaka]]'''\n| RD1-team4 = [[Minoru Fujita]]\n| RD1-score3 = Pin\n| RD1-score4 = \n| RD1-team5 = '''[[Ryuji Yamakawa]]'''\n| RD1-team6 = [[Masayoshi Motegi]]\n| RD1-score5 = Pin\n| RD1-score6 = \n| RD1-team7 = '''[[Gedo (wrestler)|Gedo]]'''\n| RD1-team8 = [[Tomoaki Honma]]\n| RD1-score7 = Pin\n| RD1-score8 = \n| RD2-team1 = '''Yoshihiro Tajiri'''\n| RD2-team2 = Minoru Tanaka\n| RD2-score1 = Pin\n| RD2-score2 = \n| RD2-team3 = Ryuji Yamakawa\n| RD2-team4 = '''Gedo'''\n| RD2-score3 = Pin\n| RD2-score4 = \n| RD3-team1 = '''Yoshihiro Tajiri'''\n| RD3-team2 = Gedo\n| RD3-score1 = Pin\n| RD3-score2 = \n}}\n\n===BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Championship Tournament (1998)===\nThe '''BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Championship Tournament''' was held to crown the inaugural [[BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Championship|BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Champion]] from June 8 to August 9, 1998.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Death Match Title Tournament 1998 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/title.html#death |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{8TeamBracket-NoSeeds\n| RD1=Quarterfinals\n| RD2=Semifinals\n| RD3=Final\n| RD1-team1 = '''[[Mitsuhiro Matsunaga]]'''\n| RD1-team2 = Jason the Terrible\n| RD1-score1 = Pin\n| RD1-score2 = 14:29\n| RD1-team3 = '''Shadow Winger'''\n| RD1-team4 = Shoji Nakamaki\n| RD1-score3 = Pin\n| RD1-score4 = 7:29\n| RD1-team5 = '''[[Mr. Pogo|The Great Pogo]]'''\n| RD1-team6 = [[Great Kojika|Kung Fu Lee]]\n| RD1-score5 = Pin\n| RD1-score6 = 9:23\n| RD1-team7 = '''[[Shadow WX]]'''\n| RD1-team8 = [[Tomoaki Honma]]\n| RD1-score7 = Pin\n| RD1-score8 = 16:22\n| RD2-team1 = '''Mitsuhiro Matsunaga'''\n| RD2-team2 = Shadow Winger\n| RD2-score1 = Pin\n| RD2-score2 = 10:21\n| RD2-team3 = '''The Great Pogo'''\n| RD2-team4 = Shadow WX\n| RD2-score3 = Pin\n| RD2-score4 = 15:02\n| RD3-team1 = Mitsuhiro Matsunaga\n| RD3-team2 = '''The Great Pogo'''\n| RD3-score1 = Pin\n| RD3-score2 = 8:36\n}}\n\n===BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship Tournament (1999)===\nThe '''BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship Tournament''' was a [[round-robin tournament]] for the vacant [[BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship (1998\u20132002)|BJW Junior Heavyweight Championship]] held between June 14 and June 30, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Junior Heavyweight Title League 1999 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/title.html#junior99 |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;text-align:center\"\n|+Final standings\n|-\n![[Masayoshi Motegi]]\n|9\n|-\n![[Abdullah Kobayashi|Abdullah Junior Kobayashi]]\n|8\n|-\n![[Men's Teioh]]\n|7\n|-\n!The Winger\n|7\n|-\n!Fantastik\n|7\n|-\n!Super Perro\n|4\n|-\n![[Jun Kasai]]\n|0\n|}\n<center>\n{{2TeamBracket\n| RD1=Final\n| RD1-seed1=\n| RD1-team1='''Masayoshi Motegi'''\n| RD1-seed2=\n| RD1-team2=Abdullah Junior Kobayashi\n| RD1-score1=Pin\n| RD1-score2=13:19\n}}\n</center>\n\n===Grand Prix Tournament===\nThe '''Grand Prix Tournament''' was a single elimination tournament which took place between January 2, 2000 and February 22, 2000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grand Prix Tournament 2000 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/misc.html#grandprix |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{8TeamBracket-NoSeeds\n| RD1=Quarterfinals\n| RD2=Semifinals\n| RD3=Final\n| RD1-team1 = '''Mike Samples'''\n| RD1-team2 = Daikokubo Benkei\n| RD1-score1 = Pin\n| RD1-score2 = 10:12\n| RD1-team3 = [[Ryuji Yamakawa]]\n| RD1-team4 = '''[[Tomoaki Honma]]*'''\n| RD1-score3 = Pin\n| RD1-score4 = 23:45\n| RD1-team5 = '''[[Julio Estrada (wrestler)|Crazy Sheik]]'''\n| RD1-team6 = [[Jun Kasai]]\n| RD1-score5 = Pin\n| RD1-score6 = 7:53\n| RD1-team7 = '''[[Shadow WX]]'''\n| RD1-team8 = The Winger\n| RD1-score7 = Pin\n| RD1-score8 = 12:28\n| RD2-team1 = '''Mike Samples'''\n| RD2-team2 = Tomoaki Honma\n| RD2-score1 = Pin\n| RD2-score2 = 16:35\n| RD2-team3 = Crazy Sheik\n| RD2-team4 = '''Shadow WX'''\n| RD2-score3 = Pin\n| RD2-score4 = 10:18\n| RD3-team1 = '''Mike Samples'''\n| RD3-team2 = Shadow WX\n| RD3-score1 = Pin\n| RD3-score2 = 10:36\n}}\n*Yamakawa's [[BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Championship]] was on the line.\n\n===Super J-Cup Qualifying Tournament===\nThe '''Super J-Cup Qualifying Tournament''' was a tournament for [[Cruiserweight (professional wrestling)|junior heavyweight wrestlers]] with the winner qualifying for the [[Super J-Cup (2000)|2000 Super J-Cup]], representing BJW in the tournament. The tournament was held between February 23 and March 3, 2000.<ref>{{cite web |title=J Cup Big Japan Qualification Tournament 2000 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/misc.html#jcup |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{3RoundBracket-Byesnoseeds\n|RD1-team3=[[Ryuji Ito]]\n|RD1-team4='''[[Men's Teioh]]'''\n|RD1-team5='''[[Masayoshi Motegi]]'''\n|RD1-team6=The Winger\n|RD1-team7=\n|RD1-team8=\n|RD2-team1=Guerrero del Futuro\n|RD2-team2='''Men's Teioh'''\n|RD2-team3='''Masayoshi Motegi'''\n|RD2-team4=Fantastik\n|RD3-team1='''Men's Teioh'''\n|RD3-team2=Masayoshi Motegi\n|RD1-score3=Pin\n|RD1-score4=11:00\n|RD1-score5=Pin\n|RD1-score6=15:22\n|RD2-score1=Pin\n|RD2-score3=Pin\n|RD3-score1=Pin\n|RD2-score2=13:02\n|RD2-score4=9:55\n|RD3-score2=8:50\n}}\n\n===2000 World Extreme Cup===\nThe '''2000 World Extreme Cup''' was a round-robin tournament contested under deathmatch variations. The tournament consisted of three blocks with each block consisting of four wrestlers and a total of twelve participants in the tournament. The top three scorers of each block qualified for the knockout stage of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Extreme Cup 2000|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/wec.html#cup2000|publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Final standings\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Block A !! colspan=\"2\" | Block B !! colspan=\"2\" | Block C\n|-\n!Tower of Doom||6!![[John Zandig]]||6!!Mike Samples||6\n|-\n![[Ryuji Yamakawa]]||4!![[Julio Estrada (wrestler)|Crazy Sheik]]||4!![[Shadow WX]]||4\n|-\n![[Mustafa Saed]]||2!!Winger||2!![[Tomoaki Honma]]||2\n|-\n![[Harley Lewis]]||0!!Terry Bull||0!![[Wifebeater (wrestler)|Wifebeater]]||0\n|}\n<center>\n{{8TeamBracket-NoSeeds\n| RD1=Quarterfinals\n| RD2=Semifinals\n| RD3=Final\n|RD1-team1='''Shadow WX'''\n|RD1-team2=Tower of Doom\n|RD1-team3='''Crazy Sheik'''\n|RD1-team4=Mustafa Saed\n|RD1-team5='''Tomoaki Honma'''\n|RD1-team6=Mike Samples\n|RD1-team7=Ryuji Yamakawa\n|RD1-team8='''John Zandig'''\n|RD2-team1='''Shadow WX'''\n|RD2-team2=Crazy Sheik\n|RD2-team3='''Tomoaki Honma'''\n|RD2-team4=John Zandig\n|RD3-team1='''Shadow WX'''\n|RD3-team2=John Zandig\n}}\n</center>\n\n===BJW Heavyweight Championship Tournament===\nThe '''BJW Heavyweight Championship Tournament''' was held between March 18 and March 20, 2001 to determine the inaugural [[BJW Heavyweight Championship|BJW Heavyweight Champion]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Title Tournament 2001|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/title.html#title|publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{8TeamBracket-NoSeeds\n| RD1=Quarterfinals\n| RD2=Semifinals\n| RD3=Final\n|RD1-team1='''[[Wifebeater (wrestler)|Wifebeater]]'''\n|RD1-team2=[[Ryuji Yamakawa]]\n|RD1-team3='''KAMIKAZE'''\n|RD1-team4=[[Mad Man Pondo]]\n|RD1-team5=[[Shadow WX]]\n|RD1-team6='''Daikokubo Benkei'''\n|RD1-team7='''[[John Zandig]]'''\n|RD1-team8=[[Daisuke Sekimoto]]\n|RD2-team1=Wifebeater\n|RD2-team2='''KAMIKAZE'''\n|RD2-team3=Daikokubo Benkei\n|RD2-team4='''John Zandig'''\n|RD3-team1='''KAMIKAZE'''\n|RD3-team2=John Zandig\n|RD1-score1=Referee stoppage\n|RD1-score2=8:33\n|RD1-score3=Pin\n|RD1-score4=6:33\n|RD1-score5=Pin\n|RD1-score7=Pin\n|RD1-score6=8:48\n|RD1-score8=7:12\n|RD2-score1=Pin\n|RD2-score2=5:50\n|RD2-score3=Pin\n|RD2-score4=4:09\n|RD3-score1=Pin\n|RD3-score2=5:38\n}}\n\n===BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Championship Tournament (2001)===\nA tournament was held to crown a new [[BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Championship|BJW Deathmatch Heavyweight Champion]] after previous champion [[Tomoaki Honma]] left the company in March 2001, thus vacating the title. The tournament was held between April 28 and May 4, 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Death Match Title Tournament 2001|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/title.html#death2001|publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{4RoundBracket-Byes\n|RD2=Quarterfinals\n|RD1-team03='''KAMIKAZE'''\n|RD1-team04=[[Jun Kasai]]\n|RD1-team05='''[[John Zandig]]'''\n|RD1-team06=[[Mad Man Pondo]]\n|RD1-team09=[[Abdullah Kobayashi]]\n|RD1-team10='''[[Kouhiro Kanemura|Kintaro Kanemura]]'''\n|RD1-team13='''Winger'''\n|RD1-team14=[[Shadow WX]]\n|RD2-team01='''[[Justice Pain]]'''\n|RD2-team02=KAMIKAZE\n|RD2-team03='''John Zandig'''\n|RD2-team04=BYE\n|RD2-team05='''Kintaro Kanemura'''\n|RD2-team06=BYE\n|RD2-team07='''Winger'''\n|RD2-team08=[[Wifebeater (wrestler)|Wifebeater]]\n|RD3-team01=Justice Pain\n|RD3-team02='''John Zandig'''\n|RD3-team03='''Kintaro Kanemura'''\n|RD3-team04=Winger\n|RD4-team01='''John Zandig'''\n|RD4-team02=Kintaro Kanemura\n}}\n\n===Six-Man Maximum Tag League===\nThe '''Six-Man Tag Team League''' was a round-robin tournament featuring four trios with each trio consisting of three wrestlers and the tournament featured [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|six-man tag team matches]]. The tournament was held between October 15 and October 25, 2001. The tournament was won by the trio of KAMIKAZE, [[Hideki Hosaka]] and Shunme Matsuzaki.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Six Man Tag League 2001|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/sixtag.html#2001|publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;text-align:center\"\n|+Final standings\n|-\n!KAMIKAZE, [[Hideki Hosaka]] and Shunme Matsuzaki\n|5\n|-\n![[Men's Teioh]], [[Daisuke Sekimoto]] and [[Ryuji Ito]]<br>{{small|(Men's Club)}}\n|4\n|-\n![[Jun Kasai]], [[Mad Man Pondo]] and [[Ruckus (wrestler)|Ruckus]]\n|2\n|-\n!Daikokubo Benkei, [[Abdullah Kobayashi]] and [[Jaki Numazawa|Naoki Numazawa]]<br>{{small|(Skinheads)}}\n|0\n|}\n\n===2002 World Extreme Cup===\nThe 2002 World Extreme Cup was the second version of the World Extreme Cup tournament consisting of four blocks and four wrestlers in each block, a total of sixteen participants in the tournament. The top two wrestlers from each block qualified for the knockout stage of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Extreme Cup 2002|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/wec.html#cup2002|publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Final standings\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Block A !! colspan=\"2\" | Block B !! colspan=\"2\" | Block C !! colspan=\"2\" | Block D\n|-\n!Tower of Doom||4!![[Homicide (wrestler)|Homicide]]||4!!Mamushi||6!![[Abdullah Kobayashi]]||6\n|-\n![[Ryuji Yamakawa|Seiji Yamakawa]]||4!![[Hido (wrestler)|Bad Boy Hido]]||4!![[Kouhiro Kanemura|Kintaro Kanemura]]||4!![[Mad Man Pondo]]||4\n|-\n!Winger||4!![[2 Tuff Tony]]||2!![[Dudley Dudley (wrestler)|O.D.D.]]||2!!Biomonster DNA||2\n|-\n!Mike Samples||0!![[Shadow WX]]||2!!Mark Manson||0!![[Axl Rotten]]||0\n|}\n<center>\n{{8TeamBracket-NoSeeds\n| RD1=Quarterfinals\n| RD2=Semifinals\n| RD3=Final\n|RD1-team1='''Winger'''\n|RD1-team2=Homicide\n|RD1-team3='''Seiji Yamakawa'''\n|RD1-team4=Bad Boy Hido\n|RD1-team5='''Shadow WX'''\n|RD1-team6=Mad Man Pondo\n|RD1-team7=Abdullah Kobayashi\n|RD1-team8='''Kintaro Kanemura'''\n|RD2-team1=Winger\n|RD2-team2='''Seiji Yamakawa'''\n|RD2-team3=Shadow WX\n|RD2-team4='''Kintaro Kanemura'''\n|RD3-team1='''Seiji Yamakawa'''\n|RD3-team2=Kintaro Kanemura\n}}\n</center>\n\n===Hayabusa Cup===\nThe '''Hayabusa Cup''' was a round-robin tournament which took place between April 14 and May 6, 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hayabusa Cup 2002 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/misc.html#hayabusa |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The tournament was held as a homage to [[Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling]] superstar [[Hayabusa (wrestler)|Hayabusa]], who had recently retired from wrestling due to a severe injury which left him paralysed for the rest of his life.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;text-align:center\"\n|+Final standings\n|-\n![[Ryuji Ito]]\n|8\n|-\n!Satoru Makita\n|8\n|-\n!Daisaku Shimoda\n|7\n|-\n!Katsumasa Inoue\n|2\n|-\n!Naoki Numazawa\n|2\n|-\n!Yuji Kamijo\n|1\n|}\n<center>\n{{2TeamBracket\n| RD1=Final\n| RD1-seed1=\n| RD1-team1='''Ryuji Ito'''\n| RD1-seed2=\n| RD1-team2=Satoru Makita\n| RD1-score1=Pin\n| RD1-score2=10:39\n}}\n</center>\n\n===Six-Man Tag Team Tournament===\nA knockout tournament was held on June 13, 2004 featuring six-man tag team matches.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Japan Six Man Tag Tournament 2004|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/sixtag.html#2004|publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{3RoundBracket-Byesnoseeds\n|RD1-Quarterfinals\n|RD2-Semifinals\n|RD3-Final\n|RD1-team1='''[[Kengo Mashimo]], Manabu Hara and [[Shiori Asahi]]'''\n|RD1-team2=Kudo, Daichi Kakimoto and TA*KU\n|RD1-team3='''[[Harashima|Hero!]], [[Jaki Numazawa]] and Super-X'''\n|RD1-team4=Kunio Toshima, Katsumasa Inoue and [[Mineo Fujita]]\n|RD1-team7='''[[Daisuke Sekimoto]], Futoshi Miwa and Kyosuke Sasaki'''\n|RD1-team8=Kazuhiro Tamura, Masanori Ishikura and [[Yuji Hino]]\n|RD2-team1=Kengo Mashimo, Manabu Hara and Shiori Asahi\n|RD2-team2='''Hero!, Jaki Numazawa and Super-X'''\n|RD2-team3='''Daisuke Sekimoto, Futoshi Miwa and Kyosuke Sasaki'''\n|RD2-team4=[[Shuji Ishikawa]], Hajime Moriyama and Kent\n|RD3-team1='''Hero!, Jaki Numazawa and Super-X'''\n|RD3-team2=Daisuke Sekimoto, Futoshi Miwa and Kyosuke Sasaki\n}}\n\n===Number 1 of Japan Tournament===\nThe '''Number 1 of Japan Tournament''' was held on September 5, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Number 1 of Japan Tournament 2004 |url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/garbage/bjw/misc.html#number |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{3RoundBracket-Byesnoseeds\n|RD1-team3=[[Abdullah Kobayashi]]\n|RD1-team4='''[[Jaki Numazawa]]'''\n|RD1-team5='''Katsumasa Inoue'''\n|RD1-team6=[[Shadow WX]]\n|RD1-team7=\n|RD1-team8=\n|RD2-team1=[[Ryuji Yamakawa]]\n|RD2-team2='''Jaki  Numazawa'''\n|RD2-team3=Katsumasa Inoue\n|RD2-team4='''[[Daisuke Sekimoto]]'''\n