{"title_page": "Cytokine release syndrome", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Cytokine release syndrome (CRS)\n| synonyms        = Infusion-related reaction (IRR), infusion reaction,<ref name=Vog2010/> cytokine storm<ref name=EMAws2010 />\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Immunology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Cytokine release syndrome''' ('''CRS''') or '''cytokine storm syndrome''' ('''CSS''') is a form of [[systemic inflammatory response syndrome]] (SIRS) that can be triggered by a variety of factors such as infections and certain drugs.<ref>{{cite journal |display-authors=3 |vauthors=Shimabukuro-Vornhagen A, G\u00f6del P, Subklewe M, Stemmler HJ, Schl\u00f6\u00dfer HA |title=Cytokine release syndrome |journal=J Immunotherapy Cancer |date=15 June 2018 |volume=6 |pages=56 |doi=10.1186/s40425-018-0343-9 |pmid=29907163 |pmc=6003181}}</ref> It occurs when large numbers of [[white blood cell]]s are activated and release [[inflammatory cytokine]]s, which in turn activate yet more white blood cells. CRS is also an [[adverse effect]] of some [[monoclonal antibody]] drugs, as well as [[Cancer immunotherapy#Adoptive T-cell therapy|adoptive T-cell therapies]].<ref name=Blood2014>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lee DW, Gardner R, Porter DL, Louis CU, Ahmed N, Jensen M, Grupp SA, Mackall CL | title = Current concepts in the diagnosis and management of cytokine release syndrome | journal = Blood | volume = 124 | issue = 2 | pages = 188\u201395 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24876563 | pmc = 4093680 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2014-05-552729 }}</ref><ref name=Kroschinsky2017rev>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kroschinsky F, St\u00f6lzel F, von Bonin S, Beutel G, Kochanek M, Kiehl M, Schellongowski P | title = New drugs, new toxicities: severe side effects of modern targeted and immunotherapy of cancer and their management | journal = Critical Care | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 89 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28407743 | pmc = 5391608 | doi = 10.1186/s13054-017-1678-1 }}</ref> Severe cases have been called '''cytokine storms'''.<ref name=EMAws2010>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vidal JM, Kawabata TT, Thorpe R, Silva-Lima B, Cederbrant K, Poole S, Mueller-Berghaus J, Pallardy M, Van der Laan JW | title = In vitro cytokine release assays for predicting cytokine release syndrome: the current state-of-the-science. Report of a European Medicines Agency Workshop | journal = Cytokine | volume = 51 | issue = 2 | pages = 213\u201315 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 20471854 | doi = 10.1016/j.cyto.2010.04.008 }}</ref> When occurring as a result of drug administration, it is also known as an '''infusion reaction'''.<ref name=Vog2010>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vogel WH | title = Infusion reactions: diagnosis, assessment, and management | journal = Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing | volume = 14 | issue = 2 | pages = E10\u201321 | date = April 2010 | pmid = 20350882 | doi = 10.1188/10.CJON.E10-E21 }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nSymptoms include fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, muscle and joint pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, rashes, fast breathing, rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure, seizures, headache, confusion, delirium, hallucinations, tremor, and loss of coordination.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\nLab tests and clinical monitoring show low blood oxygen, widened pulse pressure, increased cardiac output (early), potentially diminished cardiac output (late), [[Azotemia|high levels of nitrogen compounds in the blood]], elevated [[D-dimer]], [[elevated transaminases]], [[Complement factor I|factor I deficiency]] and excessive bleeding, [[Bilirubin#Hyperbilirubinemia|higher-than-normal level of bilirubin]].<ref name=Blood2014/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bonifant CL, Jackson HJ, Brentjens RJ, Curran KJ | title = Toxicity and management in CAR T-cell therapy | journal = Molecular Therapy Oncolytics | volume = 3 | pages = 16011 | date = 2016 | pmid = 27626062 | pmc = 5008265 | doi = 10.1038/mto.2016.11 }}</ref>\n\n==Cause==\nCRS occurs when large numbers of [[white blood cell]]s, including [[B cells]], [[T cells]], [[natural killer cells]], [[macrophages]], [[dendritic cells]], and [[monocytes]] are activated and release [[inflammatory cytokine]]s, which activate more white blood cells in a positive feedback loop of pathogenic inflammation.<ref name=Blood2014/> Immune cells are activated by stressed or infected cells through receptor-ligand interactions.<ref name=\"Liu Zhou Yang 2013 p. \">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu Q, Zhou YH, Yang ZQ | title = The cytokine storm of severe influenza and development of immunomodulatory therapy | journal = Cellular & Molecular Immunology | volume = 13 | issue = 1 | pages = 3\u201310 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26189369 | pmc = 4711683 | doi = 10.1038/cmi.2015.74 }}</ref>\n\nThis can occur when the [[immune system]] is fighting [[pathogen]]s, as cytokines produced by immune cells recruit more effector immune cells such as [[T-cell]]s and inflammatory monocytes (which differentiate into [[macrophage]]s) to the site of inflammation or infection.  In addition, pro-inflammatory cytokines binding their cognate receptor on immune cells results in activation and stimulation of further cytokine production.<ref name=\"janeway\">{{cite book | vauthors = Murphy K, Travers P, Walport M | title = Janeway's Immunobiology. | edition = 7th | publisher = Garland | location = London | year = 2007 | chapter = Signaling Through Immune System Receptors | isbn = 978-0-8153-4123-9 | chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/janewaysimmunobi00murp }}</ref> This process, when dysregulated, can be life-threatening due to systemic hyper-inflammation, hypotensive shock, and multi-organ failure. \n\n[[Adoptive cell transfer]] of autologous T-cells modified with [[chimeric antigen receptor]]s (CAR-T cell therapy) also causes CRS.<ref name=Blood2014/> Serum samples of patients with CAR-T associated CRS have elevated levels of IL-6, IFN-\u03b3, IL-8 (CXCL8), IL-10, GM-CSF, MIP-1\u03b1/\u03b2, MCP-1 (CCL2), CXCL9, and CXCL10 (IP-10).<ref name =\"Teachey2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Teachey DT et al. | title = Identification of Predictive Biomarkers for Cytokine Release Syndrome after Chimeric Antigen Receptor T-cell Therapy for Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia. | journal = Cancer Discovery | date = 2016 | pmid = 27076371 | doi = 10.1158/2159-8290.CD-16-0040 | volume = 6 | pmc = 5448406 | pages = 664\u201379}}</ref> The most predictive biomarkers 36h after CAR-T infusion of CRS are a fever \u226538.9\u00b0C and elevated levels of MCP-1 in serum.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hay KA et al. | title = Kinetics and biomarkers of severe cytokine release syndrome after CD19 chimeric antigen receptor-modified T-cell therapy. | journal = Blood. | date = 2017 | pmid = 28924019 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2017-06-793141 | volume = 130 | pmc = 5701525 | pages = 2295\u20132306}}</ref> Many of the cytokines elevated in CRS are not produced by CAR-T cells, but by myeloid cells that are pathogenically licensed through T-cell-mediated activating mechanisms. For example, [[in vitro]] co-culture experiments have demonstrated IL-6, MCP-1, and MIP-1 are not produced by CAR-T cells, but rather by inflammatory myeloid lineage cells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Barrett DM et al. | title = Interleukin 6 Is Not Made By Chimeric Antigen Receptor T Cells and Does Not Impact Their Function. | journal = Blood| date = 2016 | url = https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/128/22/654/99086/Interleukin-6-Is-Not-Made-By-Chimeric-Antigen}}</ref> [[In vivo]] models have demonstrated NSG (NOD/SCID/\u03b3-chain deficient mice) with defects of both lymphocyte and myeloid lineage compartments do not develop CRS after CAR-T cell infusion.<ref name =\"Sentman\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sentman ML et al. | display-authors = 1 | title = Mechanisms of Acute Toxicity in NKG2D Chimeric Antigen Receptor T Cell-Treated Mice. | journal = J Immunol. | date = 2016 | pmid = 27849169 | doi = 10.4049/jimmunol.1600769 | volume = 197 | pmc = 5136298 | pages = 4674\u201385}}</ref> As a result, therapeutics to prevent or manage CRS largely focus on inhibition CAR-T cell cross-talk with inflammatory myeloid cells or blockade of downstream myeloid-derived cytokines.\n\nKey therapeutic targets to abrogate hyper-inflammation in CRS are IL-1, IL-6, and GM-CSF. An [[in vivo]] model found that GM-CSF knockout CAR-T cells do not induce CRS in mice. However, IL-1 knockout and IL-6 knockout hosts (whose myeloid cells are deficient in IL-1 and IL-6, respectively) were susceptible to CRS after the administration of wild-type CAR-T cells.<ref name=Sentman/> It is thought this may be because while blockade of IL-1 and IL-6 are myeloid-derived cytokines are thus too far downstream of the inflammatory cascade. Moreover, while [[tocilizumab]] (anti-IL-6R monoclonal antibody) may have an anti-inflammatory and antipyretic effect, it has been shown to increase serum levels of IL-6 by saturating the receptor, thus driving the cytokine across the [[blood brain barrier]] (BBB) and worsening neurotoxicity.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Santomasso BD et al. | display-authors = 1 | title = Clinical and Biological Correlates of Neurotoxicity Associated with CAR T-cell Therapy in Patients with B-cell Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia. | journal = Cancer Discovery | date = 2018 | url = https://cancerdiscovery.aacrjournals.org/content/8/8/958}}</ref> Monoclonal antibody blockade of GM-CSF with [[lenzilumab]] has been demonstrated to protect mice from CAR-T associated CRS and neurotoxicity while maintaining anti-leukemic efficacy.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sterner RM et al. | display-authors = 1 | title = GM-CSF inhibition reduces cytokine release syndrome and neuroinflammation but enhances CAR-T cell function in xenografts. | journal = Blood. | date = 2019 | pmid = 30463995 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2018-10-881722 | volume = 133 | pmc = 6376281 | pages = 697\u2013709}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to adoptive T-cell therapies, severe CRS or cytokine reactions can occur in a number of infectious and non-infectious diseases including [[graft-versus-host disease]] (GVHD), [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]] (ARDS), [[sepsis]], [[Ebola]], [[avian influenza]], [[smallpox]], and [[systemic inflammatory response syndrome]] (SIRS).<ref name=\"goldman\" />\n\nAlthough, [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2) is sufficiently cleared by the early acute phase anti-viral response in most individuals, some progress to a hyperinflammatory condition, often with life-threatening pulmonary involvement. This systemic hyperinflammation results in inflammatory lymphocytic and monocytic infiltration of the lung and the heart, causing ARDS and cardiac failure. Patients with fulminant COVID-19 and ARDS have classical serum biomarkers of CRS including elevated CRP, LDH, IL-6, and ferritin.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhang C et al. | title = The cytokine release syndrome (CRS) of severe COVID-19 and Interleukin-6 receptor (IL-6R) antagonist Tocilizumab may be the key to reduce the mortality | journal = International Journal of Antimicrobial Agents | url = https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0924857920301047}}</ref> \n\n[[Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis]] and [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein-Barr virus-related hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis|Epstein-Barr virus-related hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis]] are caused by extreme elevations in cytokines and can be regarded as one form of severe cytokine release syndrome.<ref name=\"pmid29885408\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rezk SA, Zhao X, Weiss LM | title = Epstein\u2013Barr virus \u2013 associated lymphoid proliferations, a 2018 update | journal = Human Pathology | volume = 79| issue = | pages = 18\u201341| date = June 2018 | pmid = 29885408 | doi = 10.1016/j.humpath.2018.05.020 | url = }}</ref> \n\nCytokine reaction syndrome may also be induced by certain medications, such as the [[CD20]] antibody [[rituximab]] and the [[CD19]] CAR T cell [[tisagenlecleucel]]. The experimental drug [[TGN1412]]\u2014also known as Theralizumab\u2014caused extremely serious symptoms  when given to six participants in a [[Clinical trial#Phase I|Phase I trial]].<ref name=\"EMAws2010\"/> A controlled and limited CRS is triggered by active fever therapy with mixed bacterial vaccines (MBV) according to [[Coley's toxins|Coley]]; it is used for oncological and certain chronic diseases.<ref name=\"G\u00f6hring2016\">E. G\u00f6hring: ''Active Fever Therapy with MBV \u2013 Coley's Toxins: The Perfect Storm of Cytokines'', Epubli, Berlin 2019, {{ISBN|978-3748530596}}.</ref> CRS has also arisen with [[biotherapeutic]]s intended to suppress or activate the immune system through receptors on white blood cells.  [[Muromonab-CD3]], an anti-[[CD3 (immunology)|CD3]] monoclonal antibody intended to suppress the immune system to prevent rejection of [[organ transplant]]s; [[alemtuzumab]], which is anti-[[CD52]] and used to treat blood cancers as well as [[multiple sclerosis]] and in organ transplants; and [[rituximab]], which is anti-[[CD20]] and used to treat blood cancers and auto-immune disorders, all cause CRS.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nCRS needs to be distinguished from symptoms of the disease itself and, in the case of drugs, from other adverse effects\u2014for example [[tumor lysis syndrome]] requires different interventions. As of 2015, differential diagnoses depended on the judgement of doctor as there were no objective tests.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\n===Classification===\nCRS is a form of [[systemic inflammatory response syndrome]] and is an [[adverse effect]] of some drugs.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\nThe [[Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events]] classifications for CRS as of version 4.03 issued in 2010 were:<ref name=Blood2014/><ref>{{cite web|title=Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) Version v4.03|url=https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf|publisher=National Institutes of Health and National Cancer Institute|page=66|date=June 14, 2010|access-date=October 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830073206if_/https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf#page=67 |archive-date=August 30, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Grades !! Toxicity\n|-\n| Grade 1 ||Mild reaction, infusion interruption not indicated; intervention not indicated\n|-\n| Grade 2 || Therapy or infusion interruption indicated but responds promptly to symptomatic treatment (e.g., antihistamines, NSAIDS, narcotics, IV fluids); prophylactic medications indicated for <=24 hrs\n|-\n| Grade 3 ||Prolonged (e.g., not rapidly responsive to symptomatic medication or brief interruption of infusion); recurrence of symptoms following initial improvement; hospitalization indicated for clinical sequelae (e.g., renal impairment, pulmonary infiltrates)\n|-\n| Grade 4 ||Life-threatening consequences; pressor or ventilatory support indicated\n|-\n| Grade 5 ||[[Death]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Prevention==\nSevere CRS caused by some drugs can be prevented by using lower doses, infusing slowly, and administering [[anti-histamine]]s or [[corticosteroid]]s before and during administration of the drug.<ref name=Blood2014/> Additionally, blocking GM-CSF is being explored as prevention for CAR-T associated CRS, acute GVHD, and [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) induced cytokine storm and ARDS.  \n\n''[[In vitro]]'' assays have been developed to understand the risk that [[drug discovery|pre-clinical]] drug candidates might cause CRS and guide dosing for Phase I trials, and regulatory agencies expect to see results of such tests in [[investigational new drug]] applications.<ref name=EMAws2010/><ref>{{cite web|title=Guidance for Industry: Immunogenicity Assessment for Therapeutic Protein Products|url=https://www.fda.gov/media/85017/download |type= PDF |publisher=FDA|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nA modified chandler loop model can be used as a preclinical tool to assess infusion reactions.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.intimp.2017.10.021 | volume=54 | title=Extracorporeal human whole blood in motion, as a tool to predict first-infusion reactions and mechanism-of-action of immunotherapeutics | year=2018 | journal=International Immunopharmacology | pages=1\u201311 | vauthors=Fletcher EA, Eltahir M, Lindqvist F, Rieth J, T\u00f6rnqvist G, Leja-Jarblad J, Mangsbo SM }}</ref>\n\n==Management==\nTreatment for less severe CRS is [[supportive care|supportive]], addressing the symptoms like fever, muscle pain, or fatigue. Moderate CRS requires [[oxygen therapy]] and giving fluids and [[antihypotensive agent]]s to raise blood pressure. For moderate to severe CRS, the use of immunosuppressive agents like corticosteroids may be necessary, but judgment must be used to avoid negating the effect of drugs intended to activate the immune system.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\n[[Tocilizumab]], an anti-IL6 monoclonal antibody, was FDA approved for steroid-refractory CRS based on retrospective case study data.<ref name=Blood2014/><ref name=Kroschinsky2017rev/> While anecdotal evidence suggests it may be efficacious in reducing CRS, no randomized prospective trial has provided direct evidence of IL-6R blockade reducing incidence or severity of CRS. \n\n[[Lenzilumab]], may also be effective at managing cytokine release by reducing activation of myeloid cells and decreasing the production of IL-1, IL-6, MCP-1, MIP-1, and IP-10. \n\nAlthough frequently used to treat severe CRS in people with [[ARDS]], [[corticosteroids]] and [[NSAID]]s have been evaluated in [[clinical trials]] and have shown no effect on lung mechanics, gas exchange, or beneficial outcome in early established ARDS.<ref name=\"goldman\">{{cite book | last1 = Drazen | first1 = Jeffrey M. | last2 = Cecil | first2 = Russell L. | last3 = Goldman | first3 = Lee | last4 = Bennett | first4 = J. Claude | name-list-format = vanc | title = Cecil Textbook of Medicine | edition = 21st | publisher = W.B. Saunders | location = Philadelphia | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-7216-7996-9 | url = https://archive.org/details/ceciltextbookofm00ceci }}</ref>\n\n=== Research ===\nIt is demonstrated that [[probiotics]] may modulate cytokine release and inhibit the release of inflammatory cytokines.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Senok |first1=A. C. |last2=Ismaeel |first2=A. Y. |last3=Botta |first3=G. A. |title=Probiotics: facts and myths |journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection |date=1 December 2005 |volume=11 |issue=12 |pages=958\u201366 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-0691.2005.01228.x |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1198743X14623909 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en |issn=1198-743X}}</ref> For instance [[B. longum]] reduced the release of TNF-\u03b1 and IL-8 in case of an inflamed colonic [[in vitro|tissue]] alone. Probiotics and/or [[synbiotics]] reduced the expression of proinflammatory cytokines and enhanced the expression of anti-inflammatory cytokine such as IL-10.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saez-Lara |first1=Maria Jose |last2=Gomez-Llorente |first2=Carolina |last3=Plaza-Diaz |first3=Julio |last4=Gil |first4=Angel |title=The Role of Probiotic Lactic Acid Bacteria and Bifidobacteria in the Prevention and Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease and Other Related Diseases: A Systematic Review of Randomized Human Clinical Trials |journal=BioMed Research International |date=2015 |url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/bmri/2015/505878/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nSevere CRS is rare. Minor and moderate CRS are common side effects of [[Immunosuppressive drug#Antibodies|immune-modulating antibody therapies]] and [[Chimeric antigen receptor T cell#Cancer treatment|CAR-T therapies]].<ref name=Kroschinsky2017rev/>\n\n==History==\nThe first reference to the term ''cytokine storm'' in the published [[medical literature]] appears to be by Ferrara et al. in 1993 in a discussion of [[graft vs. host disease]]; a condition in which the role of excessive and self-perpetuating cytokine release had already been under discussion for many years.<ref name=Clark2007rev>{{cite journal | vauthors = Clark IA | title = The advent of the cytokine storm | journal = Immunology and Cell Biology | volume = 85 | issue = 4 | pages = 271\u201373 | date = June 2007 | pmid = 17551531 | doi = 10.1038/sj.icb.7100062 | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170505205926/http://www.nature.com:80/icb/journal/v85/n4/full/7100062a.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferrara JL, Abhyankar S, Gilliland DG | title = Cytokine storm of graft-versus-host disease: a critical effector role for interleukin-1 | journal = Transplantation Proceedings | volume = 25 | issue = 1 Pt 2 | pages = 1216\u201317 | date = February 1993 | pmid = 8442093 | doi =  }}</ref> The term next appeared in a discussion of [[pancreatitis]] in 2002, and in 2003 it was first used in reference to a reaction to an infection.<ref name=Clark2007rev/>\n\nIt is believed that cytokine storms were responsible for the disproportionate number of healthy young adult deaths during the [[1918 flu pandemic|1918 influenza pandemic]], which killed 50 to 100 million people.<ref name=\"osterholm\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Osterholm MT | title = Preparing for the next pandemic | journal = The New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 352 | issue = 18 | pages = 1839\u201342 | date = May 2005 | pmid = 15872196 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMp058068 | author-link = Michael Osterholm | citeseerx = 10.1.1.608.6200 }}</ref> In this case, a healthy immune system may have been a liability rather than an asset. Preliminary research results from [[Taiwan]] also indicated this as the probable reason for many deaths during the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] epidemic in 2003.<ref name=\"pmid15602737\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Huang KJ, Su IJ, Theron M, Wu YC, Lai SK, Liu CC, Lei HY | title = An interferon-gamma-related cytokine storm in SARS patients | journal = Journal of Medical Virology | volume = 75 | issue = 2 | pages = 185\u201394 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15602737 | doi = 10.1002/jmv.20255 }}</ref> Human deaths from the bird flu [[H5N1]] usually involve cytokine storms as well.<ref name=\"pmid18258000\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Haque A, Hober D, Kasper LH | title = Confronting potential influenza A (H5N1) pandemic with better vaccines | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 13 | issue = 10 | pages = 1512\u201318 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 18258000 | pmc = 2851514 | doi = 10.3201/eid1310.061262 }}</ref> Cytokine storm has also been implicated in [[Hantavirus|hantavirus pulmonary syndrome]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mori M, Rothman AL, Kurane I, Montoya JM, Nolte KB, Norman JE, Waite DC, Koster FT, Ennis FA | title = High levels of cytokine-producing cells in the lung tissues of patients with fatal hantavirus pulmonary syndrome | journal = The Journal of Infectious Diseases | volume = 179 | issue = 2 | pages = 295\u2013302 | date = February 1999 | pmid = 9878011 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1086/314597 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a medical study at [[Northwick Park Hospital]] in England resulted in all 6 of the volunteers given the drug [[Theralizumab|TGN1412]] becoming critically ill, with multiple organ failure, high fever, and a systemic inflammatory response.<ref name=\"LancetLEHSHR17267317\">{{cite journal | title = High stakes, high risks | journal = The Lancet. Oncology | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 85 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17267317 | doi = 10.1016/S1470-2045(07)70004-9 | last1 = The Lancet Oncology }}</ref>  [[PAREXEL|Parexel]], a company conducting trials for pharmaceutical companies, in one of its own documents, wrote about the trial and said TGN1412 could cause a cytokine storm\u2014the dangerous reaction the men experienced.<ref name=\"urlMystery over drug trial debacle deepens\">{{cite web | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn9734-mystery-over-drug-trial-debacle-deepens-.html | title = Mystery over drug trial debacle deepens | author = Coghlan A | date = 2006-08-14 | work = Health | publisher = New Scientist | pages = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = | accessdate = 2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], a number of deaths due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] have been attributable to cytokine release storms.<ref name=\"covid-1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/12/21176783/coronavirus-covid-19-deaths-china-treatment-cytokine-storm-syndrome|title=How doctors can potentially significantly reduce the number of deaths from Covid-19|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=14 March 2020|date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"covid-2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ruan Q, Yang K, Wang W, Jiang L, Song J | title = Clinical predictors of mortality due to COVID-19 based on an analysis of data of 150 patients from Wuhan, China | journal = Intensive Care Medicine | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32125452 | doi = 10.1007/s00134-020-05991-x | pmc = 7080116 }}</ref><ref name=\"covid-3\">{{cite journal |display-authors=3 | vauthors=Mehta P, McAuley DF, Brown M, Sanchez E, Tattersall RS, Manson JJ |title=COVID-19: consider cytokine storm syndromes and immunosuppression |journal=[[The Lancet]] |date=16 March 2020 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30628-0 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30628-0/fulltext |accessdate=19 March 2020 |volume=395 |pages=1033\u201334}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Macrophage activation syndrome]]\n\n== References ==\n{{HHS content|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215073709/https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf |title =Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) Version v4.03}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 34296  \n|  ICD10           =  \n|  ICD9            =  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            =  \n|  MedlinePlus     =  \n|  eMedicineSubj   =  \n|  eMedicineTopic  =  \n|  MeshID          = \n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cytokine Release Syndrome (CRS)}}\n[[Category:Immune system disorders]]\n[[Category:Syndromes affecting immunity]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Cytokine release syndrome (CRS)\n| synonyms        = Infusion-related reaction (IRR), infusion reaction,<ref name=Vog2010/> cytokine storm<ref name=EMAws2010 />\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Immunology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Cytokine release syndrome''' ('''CRS''') or '''cytokine storm syndrome''' ('''CSS''') is a form of [[systemic inflammatory response syndrome]] (SIRS) that can be triggered by a variety of factors such as infections and certain drugs.<ref>{{cite journal |display-authors=3 |vauthors=Shimabukuro-Vornhagen A, G\u00f6del P, Subklewe M, Stemmler HJ, Schl\u00f6\u00dfer HA |title=Cytokine release syndrome |journal=J Immunotherapy Cancer |date=15 June 2018 |volume=6 |pages=56 |doi=10.1186/s40425-018-0343-9 |pmid=29907163 |pmc=6003181}}</ref> It occurs when large numbers of [[white blood cell]]s are activated and release [[inflammatory cytokine]]s, which in turn activate yet more white blood cells. CRS is also an [[adverse effect]] of some [[monoclonal antibody]] drugs, as well as [[Cancer immunotherapy#Adoptive T-cell therapy|adoptive T-cell therapies]].<ref name=Blood2014>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lee DW, Gardner R, Porter DL, Louis CU, Ahmed N, Jensen M, Grupp SA, Mackall CL | title = Current concepts in the diagnosis and management of cytokine release syndrome | journal = Blood | volume = 124 | issue = 2 | pages = 188\u201395 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24876563 | pmc = 4093680 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2014-05-552729 }}</ref><ref name=Kroschinsky2017rev>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kroschinsky F, St\u00f6lzel F, von Bonin S, Beutel G, Kochanek M, Kiehl M, Schellongowski P | title = New drugs, new toxicities: severe side effects of modern targeted and immunotherapy of cancer and their management | journal = Critical Care | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 89 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28407743 | pmc = 5391608 | doi = 10.1186/s13054-017-1678-1 }}</ref> Severe cases have been called '''cytokine storms'''.<ref name=EMAws2010>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vidal JM, Kawabata TT, Thorpe R, Silva-Lima B, Cederbrant K, Poole S, Mueller-Berghaus J, Pallardy M, Van der Laan JW | title = In vitro cytokine release assays for predicting cytokine release syndrome: the current state-of-the-science. Report of a European Medicines Agency Workshop | journal = Cytokine | volume = 51 | issue = 2 | pages = 213\u201315 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 20471854 | doi = 10.1016/j.cyto.2010.04.008 }}</ref> When occurring as a result of drug administration, it is also known as an '''infusion reaction'''.<ref name=Vog2010>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vogel WH | title = Infusion reactions: diagnosis, assessment, and management | journal = Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing | volume = 14 | issue = 2 | pages = E10\u201321 | date = April 2010 | pmid = 20350882 | doi = 10.1188/10.CJON.E10-E21 }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nSymptoms include fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, muscle and joint pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, rashes, fast breathing, rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure, seizures, headache, confusion, delirium, hallucinations, tremor, and loss of coordination.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\nLab tests and clinical monitoring show low blood oxygen, widened pulse pressure, increased cardiac output (early), potentially diminished cardiac output (late), [[Azotemia|high levels of nitrogen compounds in the blood]], elevated [[D-dimer]], [[elevated transaminases]], [[Complement factor I|factor I deficiency]] and excessive bleeding, [[Bilirubin#Hyperbilirubinemia|higher-than-normal level of bilirubin]].<ref name=Blood2014/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bonifant CL, Jackson HJ, Brentjens RJ, Curran KJ | title = Toxicity and management in CAR T-cell therapy | journal = Molecular Therapy Oncolytics | volume = 3 | pages = 16011 | date = 2016 | pmid = 27626062 | pmc = 5008265 | doi = 10.1038/mto.2016.11 }}</ref>\n\n==Cause==\nCRS occurs when large numbers of [[white blood cell]]s, including [[B cells]], [[T cells]], [[natural killer cells]], [[macrophages]], [[dendritic cells]], and [[monocytes]] are activated and release [[inflammatory cytokine]]s, which activate more white blood cells in a positive feedback loop of pathogenic inflammation.<ref name=Blood2014/> Immune cells are activated by stressed or infected cells through receptor-ligand interactions.<ref name=\"Liu Zhou Yang 2013 p. \">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu Q, Zhou YH, Yang ZQ | title = The cytokine storm of severe influenza and development of immunomodulatory therapy | journal = Cellular & Molecular Immunology | volume = 13 | issue = 1 | pages = 3\u201310 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26189369 | pmc = 4711683 | doi = 10.1038/cmi.2015.74 }}</ref>\n\nThis can occur when the [[immune system]] is fighting [[pathogen]]s, as cytokines produced by immune cells recruit more effector immune cells such as [[T-cell]]s and inflammatory monocytes (which differentiate into [[macrophage]]s) to the site of inflammation or infection.  In addition, pro-inflammatory cytokines binding their cognate receptor on immune cells results in activation and stimulation of further cytokine production.<ref name=\"janeway\">{{cite book | vauthors = Murphy K, Travers P, Walport M | title = Janeway's Immunobiology. | edition = 7th | publisher = Garland | location = London | year = 2007 | chapter = Signaling Through Immune System Receptors | isbn = 978-0-8153-4123-9 | chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/janewaysimmunobi00murp }}</ref> This process, when dysregulated, can be life-threatening due to systemic hyper-inflammation, hypotensive shock, and multi-organ failure. \n\n[[Adoptive cell transfer]] of autologous T-cells modified with [[chimeric antigen receptor]]s (CAR-T cell therapy) also causes CRS.<ref name=Blood2014/> Serum samples of patients with CAR-T associated CRS have elevated levels of IL-6, IFN-\u03b3, IL-8 (CXCL8), IL-10, GM-CSF, MIP-1\u03b1/\u03b2, MCP-1 (CCL2), CXCL9, and CXCL10 (IP-10).<ref name =\"Teachey2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Teachey DT et al. | title = Identification of Predictive Biomarkers for Cytokine Release Syndrome after Chimeric Antigen Receptor T-cell Therapy for Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia. | journal = Cancer Discovery | date = 2016 | pmid = 27076371 | doi = 10.1158/2159-8290.CD-16-0040 | volume = 6 | pmc = 5448406 | pages = 664\u201379}}</ref> The most predictive biomarkers 36h after CAR-T infusion of CRS are a fever \u226538.9\u00b0C and elevated levels of MCP-1 in serum.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hay KA et al. | title = Kinetics and biomarkers of severe cytokine release syndrome after CD19 chimeric antigen receptor-modified T-cell therapy. | journal = Blood. | date = 2017 | pmid = 28924019 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2017-06-793141 | volume = 130 | pmc = 5701525 | pages = 2295\u20132306}}</ref> Many of the cytokines elevated in CRS are not produced by CAR-T cells, but by myeloid cells that are pathogenically licensed through T-cell-mediated activating mechanisms. For example, [[in vitro]] co-culture experiments have demonstrated IL-6, MCP-1, and MIP-1 are not produced by CAR-T cells, but rather by inflammatory myeloid lineage cells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Barrett DM et al. | title = Interleukin 6 Is Not Made By Chimeric Antigen Receptor T Cells and Does Not Impact Their Function. | journal = Blood| date = 2016 | url = https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/128/22/654/99086/Interleukin-6-Is-Not-Made-By-Chimeric-Antigen}}</ref> [[In vivo]] models have demonstrated NSG (NOD/SCID/\u03b3-chain deficient mice) with defects of both lymphocyte and myeloid lineage compartments do not develop CRS after CAR-T cell infusion.<ref name =\"Sentman\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sentman ML et al. | display-authors = 1 | title = Mechanisms of Acute Toxicity in NKG2D Chimeric Antigen Receptor T Cell-Treated Mice. | journal = J Immunol. | date = 2016 | pmid = 27849169 | doi = 10.4049/jimmunol.1600769 | volume = 197 | pmc = 5136298 | pages = 4674\u201385}}</ref> As a result, therapeutics to prevent or manage CRS largely focus on inhibition CAR-T cell cross-talk with inflammatory myeloid cells or blockade of downstream myeloid-derived cytokines.\n\nKey therapeutic targets to abrogate hyper-inflammation in CRS are IL-1, IL-6, and GM-CSF. An [[in vivo]] model found that GM-CSF knockout CAR-T cells do not induce CRS in mice. However, IL-1 knockout and IL-6 knockout hosts (whose myeloid cells are deficient in IL-1 and IL-6, respectively) were susceptible to CRS after the administration of wild-type CAR-T cells.<ref name=Sentman/> It is thought this may be because while blockade of IL-1 and IL-6 are myeloid-derived cytokines are thus too far downstream of the inflammatory cascade. Moreover, while [[tocilizumab]] (anti-IL-6R monoclonal antibody) may have an anti-inflammatory and antipyretic effect, it has been shown to increase serum levels of IL-6 by saturating the receptor, thus driving the cytokine across the [[blood brain barrier]] (BBB) and worsening neurotoxicity.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Santomasso BD et al. | display-authors = 1 | title = Clinical and Biological Correlates of Neurotoxicity Associated with CAR T-cell Therapy in Patients with B-cell Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia. | journal = Cancer Discovery | date = 2018 | url = https://cancerdiscovery.aacrjournals.org/content/8/8/958}}</ref> Monoclonal antibody blockade of GM-CSF with [[lenzilumab]] has been demonstrated to protect mice from CAR-T associated CRS and neurotoxicity while maintaining anti-leukemic efficacy.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sterner RM et al. | display-authors = 1 | title = GM-CSF inhibition reduces cytokine release syndrome and neuroinflammation but enhances CAR-T cell function in xenografts. | journal = Blood. | date = 2019 | pmid = 30463995 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2018-10-881722 | volume = 133 | pmc = 6376281 | pages = 697\u2013709}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to adoptive T-cell therapies, severe CRS or cytokine reactions can occur in a number of infectious and non-infectious diseases including [[graft-versus-host disease]] (GVHD), [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]] (ARDS), [[sepsis]], [[Ebola]], [[avian influenza]], [[smallpox]], and [[systemic inflammatory response syndrome]] (SIRS).<ref name=\"goldman\" />\n\nAlthough, [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2) is sufficiently cleared by the early acute phase anti-viral response in most individuals, some progress to a hyperinflammatory condition, often with life-threatening pulmonary involvement. This systemic hyperinflammation results in inflammatory lymphocytic and monocytic infiltration of the lung and the heart, causing ARDS and cardiac failure. Patients with fulminant COVID-19 and ARDS have classical serum biomarkers of CRS including elevated CRP, LDH, IL-6, and ferritin.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhang C et al. | title = The cytokine release syndrome (CRS) of severe COVID-19 and Interleukin-6 receptor (IL-6R) antagonist Tocilizumab may be the key to reduce the mortality | journal = International Journal of Antimicrobial Agents | url = https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0924857920301047}}</ref> \n\n[[Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis]] and [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein-Barr virus-related hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis|Epstein-Barr virus-related hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis]] are caused by extreme elevations in cytokines and can be regarded as one form of severe cytokine release syndrome.<ref name=\"pmid29885408\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rezk SA, Zhao X, Weiss LM | title = Epstein\u2013Barr virus \u2013 associated lymphoid proliferations, a 2018 update | journal = Human Pathology | volume = 79| issue = | pages = 18\u201341| date = June 2018 | pmid = 29885408 | doi = 10.1016/j.humpath.2018.05.020 | url = }}</ref> \n\nCytokine reaction syndrome may also be induced by certain medications, such as the [[CD20]] antibody [[rituximab]] and the [[CD19]] CAR T cell [[tisagenlecleucel]]. The experimental drug [[TGN1412]]\u2014also known as Theralizumab\u2014caused extremely serious symptoms  when given to six participants in a [[Clinical trial#Phase I|Phase I trial]].<ref name=\"EMAws2010\"/> A controlled and limited CRS is triggered by active fever therapy with mixed bacterial vaccines (MBV) according to [[Coley's toxins|Coley]]; it is used for oncological and certain chronic diseases.<ref name=\"G\u00f6hring2016\">E. G\u00f6hring: ''Active Fever Therapy with MBV \u2013 Coley's Toxins: The Perfect Storm of Cytokines'', Epubli, Berlin 2019, {{ISBN|978-3748530596}}.</ref> CRS has also arisen with [[biotherapeutic]]s intended to suppress or activate the immune system through receptors on white blood cells.  [[Muromonab-CD3]], an anti-[[CD3 (immunology)|CD3]] monoclonal antibody intended to suppress the immune system to prevent rejection of [[organ transplant]]s; [[alemtuzumab]], which is anti-[[CD52]] and used to treat blood cancers as well as [[multiple sclerosis]] and in organ transplants; and [[rituximab]], which is anti-[[CD20]] and used to treat blood cancers and auto-immune disorders, all cause CRS.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nCRS needs to be distinguished from symptoms of the disease itself and, in the case of drugs, from other adverse effects\u2014for example [[tumor lysis syndrome]] requires different interventions. As of 2015, differential diagnoses depended on the judgement of doctor as there were no objective tests.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\n===Classification===\nCRS is a form of [[systemic inflammatory response syndrome]] and is an [[adverse effect]] of some drugs.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\nThe [[Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events]] classifications for CRS as of version 4.03 issued in 2010 were:<ref name=Blood2014/><ref>{{cite web|title=Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) Version v4.03|url=https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf|publisher=National Institutes of Health and National Cancer Institute|page=66|date=June 14, 2010|access-date=October 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830073206if_/https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf#page=67 |archive-date=August 30, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Grades !! Toxicity\n|-\n| Grade 1 ||Mild reaction, infusion interruption not indicated; intervention not indicated\n|-\n| Grade 2 || Therapy or infusion interruption indicated but responds promptly to symptomatic treatment (e.g., antihistamines, NSAIDS, narcotics, IV fluids); prophylactic medications indicated for <=24 hrs\n|-\n| Grade 3 ||Prolonged (e.g., not rapidly responsive to symptomatic medication or brief interruption of infusion); recurrence of symptoms following initial improvement; hospitalization indicated for clinical sequelae (e.g., renal impairment, pulmonary infiltrates)\n|-\n| Grade 4 ||Life-threatening consequences; pressor or ventilatory support indicated\n|-\n| Grade 5 ||[[Death]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Prevention==\nSevere CRS caused by some drugs can be prevented by using lower doses, infusing slowly, and administering [[anti-histamine]]s or [[corticosteroid]]s before and during administration of the drug.<ref name=Blood2014/> Additionally, blocking GM-CSF is being explored as prevention for CAR-T associated CRS, acute GVHD, and [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) induced cytokine storm and ARDS.  \n\n''[[In vitro]]'' assays have been developed to understand the risk that [[drug discovery|pre-clinical]] drug candidates might cause CRS and guide dosing for Phase I trials, and regulatory agencies expect to see results of such tests in [[investigational new drug]] applications.<ref name=EMAws2010/><ref>{{cite web|title=Guidance for Industry: Immunogenicity Assessment for Therapeutic Protein Products|url=https://www.fda.gov/media/85017/download |type= PDF |publisher=FDA|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nA modified chandler loop model can be used as a preclinical tool to assess infusion reactions.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.intimp.2017.10.021 | volume=54 | title=Extracorporeal human whole blood in motion, as a tool to predict first-infusion reactions and mechanism-of-action of immunotherapeutics | year=2018 | journal=International Immunopharmacology | pages=1\u201311 | vauthors=Fletcher EA, Eltahir M, Lindqvist F, Rieth J, T\u00f6rnqvist G, Leja-Jarblad J, Mangsbo SM }}</ref>\n\n==Management==\nTreatment for less severe CRS is [[supportive care|supportive]], addressing the symptoms like fever, muscle pain, or fatigue. Moderate CRS requires [[oxygen therapy]] and giving fluids and [[antihypotensive agent]]s to raise blood pressure. For moderate to severe CRS, the use of immunosuppressive agents like corticosteroids may be necessary, but judgment must be used to avoid negating the effect of drugs intended to activate the immune system.<ref name=Blood2014/>\n\n[[Tocilizumab]], an anti-IL6 monoclonal antibody, was FDA approved for steroid-refractory CRS based on retrospective case study data.<ref name=Blood2014/><ref name=Kroschinsky2017rev/> While anecdotal evidence suggests it may be efficacious in reducing CRS, no randomized prospective trial has provided direct evidence of IL-6R blockade reducing incidence or severity of CRS. \n\n[[Lenzilumab]], may also be effective at managing cytokine release by reducing activation of myeloid cells and decreasing the production of IL-1, IL-6, MCP-1, MIP-1, and IP-10. \n\nAlthough frequently used to treat severe CRS in people with [[ARDS]], [[corticosteroids]] and [[NSAID]]s have been evaluated in [[clinical trials]] and have shown no effect on lung mechanics, gas exchange, or beneficial outcome in early established ARDS.<ref name=\"goldman\">{{cite book | last1 = Drazen | first1 = Jeffrey M. | last2 = Cecil | first2 = Russell L. | last3 = Goldman | first3 = Lee | last4 = Bennett | first4 = J. Claude | name-list-format = vanc | title = Cecil Textbook of Medicine | edition = 21st | publisher = W.B. Saunders | location = Philadelphia | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-7216-7996-9 | url = https://archive.org/details/ceciltextbookofm00ceci }}</ref>\n\n=== Research ===\nIt is demonstrated that [[probiotics]] may modulate cytokine release and inhibit the release of inflammatory cytokines.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Senok |first1=A. C. |last2=Ismaeel |first2=A. Y. |last3=Botta |first3=G. A. |title=Probiotics: facts and myths |journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection |date=1 December 2005 |volume=11 |issue=12 |pages=958\u201366 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-0691.2005.01228.x |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1198743X14623909 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en |issn=1198-743X}}</ref> For instance [[B. longum]] reduced the release of TNF-\u03b1 and IL-8 in case of an inflamed colonic [[in vitro|tissue]] alone. Probiotics and/or [[synbiotics]] reduced the expression of proinflammatory cytokines and enhanced the expression of anti-inflammatory cytokine such as IL-10.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saez-Lara |first1=Maria Jose |last2=Gomez-Llorente |first2=Carolina |last3=Plaza-Diaz |first3=Julio |last4=Gil |first4=Angel |title=The Role of Probiotic Lactic Acid Bacteria and Bifidobacteria in the Prevention and Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease and Other Related Diseases: A Systematic Review of Randomized Human Clinical Trials |journal=BioMed Research International |date=2015 |url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/bmri/2015/505878/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nSevere CRS is rare. Minor and moderate CRS are common side effects of [[Immunosuppressive drug#Antibodies|immune-modulating antibody therapies]] and [[Chimeric antigen receptor T cell#Cancer treatment|CAR-T therapies]].<ref name=Kroschinsky2017rev/>\n\n==History==\nThe first reference to the term ''cytokine storm'' in the published [[medical literature]] appears to be by Ferrara et al. in 1993 in a discussion of [[graft vs. host disease]]; a condition in which the role of excessive and self-perpetuating cytokine release had already been under discussion for many years.<ref name=Clark2007rev>{{cite journal | vauthors = Clark IA | title = The advent of the cytokine storm | journal = Immunology and Cell Biology | volume = 85 | issue = 4 | pages = 271\u201373 | date = June 2007 | pmid = 17551531 | doi = 10.1038/sj.icb.7100062 | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170505205926/http://www.nature.com:80/icb/journal/v85/n4/full/7100062a.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferrara JL, Abhyankar S, Gilliland DG | title = Cytokine storm of graft-versus-host disease: a critical effector role for interleukin-1 | journal = Transplantation Proceedings | volume = 25 | issue = 1 Pt 2 | pages = 1216\u201317 | date = February 1993 | pmid = 8442093 | doi =  }}</ref> The term next appeared in a discussion of [[pancreatitis]] in 2002, and in 2003 it was first used in reference to a reaction to an infection.<ref name=Clark2007rev/>\n\nIt is believed that cytokine storms were responsible for the disproportionate number of healthy young adult deaths during the [[1918 flu pandemic|1918 influenza pandemic]], which killed 50 to 100 million people.<ref name=\"osterholm\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Osterholm MT | title = Preparing for the next pandemic | journal = The New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 352 | issue = 18 | pages = 1839\u201342 | date = May 2005 | pmid = 15872196 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMp058068 | author-link = Michael Osterholm | citeseerx = 10.1.1.608.6200 }}</ref> In this case, a healthy immune system may have been a liability rather than an asset. Preliminary research results from [[Taiwan]] also indicated this as the probable reason for many deaths during the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] epidemic in 2003.<ref name=\"pmid15602737\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Huang KJ, Su IJ, Theron M, Wu YC, Lai SK, Liu CC, Lei HY | title = An interferon-gamma-related cytokine storm in SARS patients | journal = Journal of Medical Virology | volume = 75 | issue = 2 | pages = 185\u201394 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15602737 | doi = 10.1002/jmv.20255 }}</ref> Human deaths from the bird flu [[H5N1]] usually involve cytokine storms as well.<ref name=\"pmid18258000\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Haque A, Hober D, Kasper LH | title = Confronting potential influenza A (H5N1) pandemic with better vaccines | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 13 | issue = 10 | pages = 1512\u201318 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 18258000 | pmc = 2851514 | doi = 10.3201/eid1310.061262 }}</ref> Cytokine storm has also been implicated in [[Hantavirus|hantavirus pulmonary syndrome]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mori M, Rothman AL, Kurane I, Montoya JM, Nolte KB, Norman JE, Waite DC, Koster FT, Ennis FA | title = High levels of cytokine-producing cells in the lung tissues of patients with fatal hantavirus pulmonary syndrome | journal = The Journal of Infectious Diseases | volume = 179 | issue = 2 | pages = 295\u2013302 | date = February 1999 | pmid = 9878011 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1086/314597 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a medical study at [[Northwick Park Hospital]] in England resulted in all 6 of the volunteers given the drug [[Theralizumab|TGN1412]] becoming critically ill, with multiple organ failure, high fever, and a systemic inflammatory response.<ref name=\"LancetLEHSHR17267317\">{{cite journal | title = High stakes, high risks | journal = The Lancet. Oncology | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 85 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17267317 | doi = 10.1016/S1470-2045(07)70004-9 | last1 = The Lancet Oncology }}</ref>  [[PAREXEL|Parexel]], a company conducting trials for pharmaceutical companies, in one of its own documents, wrote about the trial and said TGN1412 could cause a cytokine storm\u2014the dangerous reaction the men experienced.<ref name=\"urlMystery over drug trial debacle deepens\">{{cite web | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn9734-mystery-over-drug-trial-debacle-deepens-.html | title = Mystery over drug trial debacle deepens | author = Coghlan A | date = 2006-08-14 | work = Health | publisher = New Scientist | pages = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = | accessdate = 2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], a number of deaths due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] have been attributable to cytokine release storms.<ref name=\"covid-1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/12/21176783/coronavirus-covid-19-deaths-china-treatment-cytokine-storm-syndrome|title=How doctors can potentially significantly reduce the number of deaths from Covid-19|publisher=[[Vox]]|access-date=14 March 2020|date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"covid-2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ruan Q, Yang K, Wang W, Jiang L, Song J | title = Clinical predictors of mortality due to COVID-19 based on an analysis of data of 150 patients from Wuhan, China | journal = Intensive Care Medicine | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32125452 | doi = 10.1007/s00134-020-05991-x | pmc = 7080116 }}</ref><ref name=\"covid-3\">{{cite journal |display-authors=3 | vauthors=Mehta P, McAuley DF, Brown M, Sanchez E, Tattersall RS, Manson JJ |title=COVID-19: consider cytokine storm syndromes and immunosuppression |journal=[[The Lancet]] |date=16 March 2020 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30628-0 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30628-0/fulltext |accessdate=19 March 2020 |volume=395 |pages=1033\u201334}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Macrophage activation syndrome]]\n\n== References ==\n{{HHS content|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215073709/https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf |title =Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) Version v4.03}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 34296  \n|  ICD10           =  \n|  ICD9            =  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            =  \n|  MedlinePlus     =  \n|  eMedicineSubj   =  \n|  eMedicineTopic  =  \n|  MeshID          = \n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cytokine Release Syndrome (CRS)}}\n[[Category:Immune system disorders]]\n[[Category:Syndromes affecting immunity]]\n", "name_user": "TheAwesomeHwyh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Vox\u2192Vox (website)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cytokine_release_syndrome"}
{"title_page": "Moira Shearer", "text_new": "{{short description|British ballerina and actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Moira Shearer\n| image       = File:Moira Shearer 1954.jpg\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Moira Shearer in 1954\n| birth_name  = Moira Shearer King\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1926|1|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dunfermline]], [[Fife]], Scotland\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2006|1|31|1926|1|17|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| yearsactive = 1938\u20131987\n| othername   = Lady Kennedy\n| website     =\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Sir [[Ludovic Kennedy]]|1950|2006|end=her death}}\n| children    =  4\n}}\n\n'''Moira Shearer King, Lady Kennedy''' (17 January 1926 \u2013 31 January 2006), was an internationally renowned British [[ballet|ballet dancer]] and [[actress]]. She is best remembered for her performances in [[Powell and Pressburger]]'s ''[[The Red Shoes (w1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'' (1948) and [[Michael Powell]]'s ''[[Peeping Tom (1960 film)|Peeping Tom]]'' (1960).\n\n==Early life==\nShe was born '''Moira Shearer King''' at Morton Lodge in [[Dunfermline]], [[Fife]], Scotland, the only child of civil engineer Harold Charles King and Margaret Crawford Reid, n\u00e9e Shearer.<ref name=\"CraineMackrell2010\">{{cite book|author1=Debra Craine|author2=Judith Mackrell|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Dance|url=https://archive.org/details/oxforddictionary0000crai_a8h2|url-access=registration|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-956344-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/oxforddictionary0000crai_a8h2/page/408 408]\u2013}}</ref> In 1931 her family moved to [[Ndola]], [[Northern Rhodesia]], where her father worked as a civil engineer and where she received her first dancing training under a former pupil of [[Enrico Cecchetti]].<ref name=Fisher>{{cite journal|title = Moira Shearer|publisher = Dancers of To-day|issue=|last = Fisher|first = Hugh|year = 1952}}</ref> She returned to Britain in 1936 and trained with Flora Fairbairn in London for a few months before she was accepted as a pupil by the Russian teacher [[Nicholas Legat]].<ref name=Fisher/> At his studio she met Mona Inglesby<ref name=Inglesby>{{cite journal|title = Ballet in the Blitz|publisher = Groundnut Publishing|last = Mona Inglesby with Kay Hunter|year = 2008}}</ref> who gave Shearer a part in her new ballet ''Endymion'', presented at an all star matinee at the Cambridge Theatre in 1938.<ref name=H-Taylor>{{cite journal|title = Mona Inglesby, Ballerina and Choreographer|publisher = Vawser and Wiles|last = Handley-Taylor|first = Geoffrey|year = 1947}}</ref>   After three years with Legat, she joined the [[Sadler's Wells Ballet School]]. After the outbreak of World War II, her parents took her to live in [[Scotland]].<ref name=Fisher/>  She joined Mona Inglesby's International Ballet<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = The Independent | date = 13 October 2006 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mona-inglesby-419831.html | accessdate =22 April 2010 | location=London | title=Mona Inglesby}}</ref> for its 1941 provincial tour and West End season before moving on to [[Sadler's Wells]] in 1942.\n\n==Film career==\nShearer first came to the public\u2019s attention as Posy Fossil in the advertisements for the [[Noel Streatfeild]] book ''[[Ballet Shoes (novel)|Ballet Shoes]]'' while she was training under Flora Fairbairn, a good friend of Streatfeild's.\n\nShe achieved international success with her first film role as Victoria Page in the [[Michael Powell|Powell]] & [[Emeric Pressburger|Pressburger]] [[ballet]]-themed [[film]] ''[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'', (1948).<ref name=ODNB/> Even her hair matched the titular footwear, and the role and film were so powerful that although she went on to star in other films and worked as a dancer for many decades, she is primarily known for playing \"Vicky\".\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:RedShoes2.jpg|thumb|250px|left|[[Robert Helpmann]], Shearer and [[L\u00e9onide Massine]] in ''The Red Shoes''.]] -->\n\nShearer retired from ballet in 1953, but she continued to act, appearing as Titania in ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' at the 1954 [[Edinburgh Festival]]. She worked again for Powell on ''[[The Tales of Hoffmann (film)|The Tales of Hoffmann]]'' and on the controversial film ''[[Peeping Tom (1960 film)|Peeping Tom]]'' (1960), which damaged Powell's own career.\n\nIn 1972, she was chosen by the [[BBC]] to present the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] when it was staged at the [[Usher Hall]] in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>O'Connor, John Kennedy. ''The Eurovision Song Contest: The Official History''. Carlton Books, UK. 2007. {{ISBN|978-1-84442-994-3}}.</ref> She also wrote for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' newspaper and gave talks on ballet worldwide.\n\nThe [[choreographer]] [[Gillian Lynne]] persuaded her to return to ballet in 1987 to play [[L. S. Lowry]]'s mother in ''A Simple Man'' for the [[BBC]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1950, Moira Shearer married journalist and broadcaster [[Ludovic Kennedy]]. They were married in the Chapel Royal in London's [[Hampton Court Palace]].<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=John|title=Shearer, Moira|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/article.jsp?articleid=97067&back=|website=ODNB|publisher=OUP|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=Photoplay>{{cite journal|title=Moira of the Red Shoes|journal=Photoplay|date=1950}}</ref> She and Kennedy had a son, Alastair, and three daughters, Ailsa, Rachel, and Fiona. Shearer died at the [[Radcliffe Infirmary]], [[Oxford]], [[England]] at the age of 80.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/02/arts/02shearer.html Obituary] in ''[[The New York Times]]'', 2 February 2006. Retrieved 11 October 2014.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1948 || ''{{sort|red|[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]}}'' || {{sort|page|Victoria Page}} ||\n|-\n| 1951 || ''{{sort|tales|[[The Tales of Hoffmann (film)|The Tales of Hoffmann]]}}'' || Stella / Olympia ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''{{sort|story|[[The Story of Three Loves]]}}'' || {{sort|wood|Paula Woodward}} || (segment \"The Jealous Lover\")\n|-\n| 1955 || ''{{sort|man|[[The Man Who Loved Redheads]]}}'' || Sylvia / Daphne / Olga / Colette ||\n|-\n| 1960 || ''[[Peeping Tom (1960 film)|Peeping Tom]]'' || Vivian ||\n|-\n| 1961 || ''[[Black Tights]]'' || Roxane ||\n|-\n| 1987 || ''{{sort|simp|A Simple Man}}'' || Mother || TV movie, final film role\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Eurovision Song Contest presenters]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0790452}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://www.ballerinagallery.com/shearer.htm The Ballerina Gallery \u2013 Moira Shearer]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/2280620.stm BBC Obituary of Moira Shearer]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1509410/Moira-Shearer.html \"The Daily Telegraph\" Obituary of Moira Shearer]\n* [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article724660.ece/ The Times Online obituary of Moira Shearer]\n* {{Find a Grave|13202082}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before={{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Bernadette N\u00ed Ghallch\u00f3ir]] |\n  title=[[Eurovision Song Contest|Eurovision Song Contest presenter]] |\n  years=[[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]] |\n  after={{flagicon|Luxembourg}} [[Helga Guitton]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shearer, Moira}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dancers of The Royal Ballet]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bearsden Academy]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dunfermline High School]]\n[[Category:People from Dunfermline]]\n[[Category:Prima ballerinas]]\n[[Category:Scottish ballerinas]]\n[[Category:Scottish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British ballerina and actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Moira Shearer\n| image       = File:Moira Shearer 1954.jpg\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Moira Shearer in 1954\n| birth_name  = Moira Shearer King\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1926|1|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dunfermline]], [[Fife]], Scotland\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2006|1|31|1926|1|17|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| yearsactive = 1938\u20131987\n| othername   = Lady Kennedy\n| website     =\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Sir [[Ludovic Kennedy]]|1950|2006|end=her death}}\n| children    =  4\n}}\n\n'''Moira Shearer King, Lady Kennedy''' (17 January 1926 \u2013 31 January 2006), was an internationally renowned British [[ballet|ballet dancer]] and [[actress]]. She is best remembered for her performances in [[Powell and Pressburger]]'s ''[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'' (1948) and [[Michael Powell]]'s ''[[Peeping Tom (1960 film)|Peeping Tom]]'' (1960).\n\n==Early life==\nShe was born '''Moira Shearer King''' at Morton Lodge in [[Dunfermline]], [[Fife]], Scotland, the only child of civil engineer Harold Charles King and Margaret Crawford Reid, n\u00e9e Shearer.<ref name=\"CraineMackrell2010\">{{cite book|author1=Debra Craine|author2=Judith Mackrell|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Dance|url=https://archive.org/details/oxforddictionary0000crai_a8h2|url-access=registration|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-956344-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/oxforddictionary0000crai_a8h2/page/408 408]\u2013}}</ref> In 1931 her family moved to [[Ndola]], [[Northern Rhodesia]], where her father worked as a civil engineer and where she received her first dancing training under a former pupil of [[Enrico Cecchetti]].<ref name=Fisher>{{cite journal|title = Moira Shearer|publisher = Dancers of To-day|issue=|last = Fisher|first = Hugh|year = 1952}}</ref> She returned to Britain in 1936 and trained with Flora Fairbairn in London for a few months before she was accepted as a pupil by the Russian teacher [[Nicholas Legat]].<ref name=Fisher/> At his studio she met Mona Inglesby<ref name=Inglesby>{{cite journal|title = Ballet in the Blitz|publisher = Groundnut Publishing|last = Mona Inglesby with Kay Hunter|year = 2008}}</ref> who gave Shearer a part in her new ballet ''Endymion'', presented at an all star matinee at the Cambridge Theatre in 1938.<ref name=H-Taylor>{{cite journal|title = Mona Inglesby, Ballerina and Choreographer|publisher = Vawser and Wiles|last = Handley-Taylor|first = Geoffrey|year = 1947}}</ref>   After three years with Legat, she joined the [[Sadler's Wells Ballet School]]. After the outbreak of World War II, her parents took her to live in [[Scotland]].<ref name=Fisher/>  She joined Mona Inglesby's International Ballet<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = The Independent | date = 13 October 2006 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mona-inglesby-419831.html | accessdate =22 April 2010 | location=London | title=Mona Inglesby}}</ref> for its 1941 provincial tour and West End season before moving on to [[Sadler's Wells]] in 1942.\n\n==Film career==\nShearer first came to the public\u2019s attention as Posy Fossil in the advertisements for the [[Noel Streatfeild]] book ''[[Ballet Shoes (novel)|Ballet Shoes]]'' while she was training under Flora Fairbairn, a good friend of Streatfeild's.\n\nShe achieved international success with her first film role as Victoria Page in the [[Michael Powell|Powell]] & [[Emeric Pressburger|Pressburger]] [[ballet]]-themed [[film]] ''[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'', (1948).<ref name=ODNB/> Even her hair matched the titular footwear, and the role and film were so powerful that although she went on to star in other films and worked as a dancer for many decades, she is primarily known for playing \"Vicky\".\n<!-- Delete